from langchain_text_splitters import RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter

text="""
Generative AI represents one of the most transformative advancements in modern technology, reshaping how humans interact with machines, create content, and solve complex problems. At its core, generative AI refers to systems capable of creating new content—such as text, images, code, audio, or video—based on patterns learned from massive datasets. Unlike traditional software, which follows a rigid set of rules, generative AI systems like OpenAI’s GPT, Google’s Gemini, or Anthropic’s Claude use deep learning and neural networks to generate original outputs that mimic human creativity and reasoning. This capability has far-reaching applications across industries. In education, generative AI helps students understand difficult topics by creating personalized explanations and practice materials. In the workplace, it boosts productivity by drafting emails, summarizing documents, generating reports, or even automating customer service responses. In creative fields, it opens the door to rapid prototyping in design, story generation in writing, and soundtrack creation in music production. Moreover, in software engineering, developers now use generative AI to write boilerplate code, suggest improvements, detect bugs, and generate documentation in real-time, reducing development cycles and increasing code quality. Perhaps most impressively, generative AI supports healthcare advancements by generating medical reports, analyzing imaging data, and even assisting in drug discovery by predicting molecular structures. However, with such power comes serious responsibility. The rise of AI-generated content has sparked debates around misinformation, copyright, deepfakes, and ethical use. Concerns over data privacy, intellectual property, and algorithmic bias are becoming more urgent, prompting governments and organizations to call for stronger regulation and transparency. Additionally, as AI becomes more integrated into our daily lives, the line between human-generated and machine-generated content blurs, raising philosophical and societal questions about authenticity, creativity, and value. From a technical perspective, models like Gemini 1.5 Flash and GPT-4.5 demonstrate how large language models (LLMs) are becoming more efficient, accurate, and multimodal—able to handle text, images, and even video inputs. These models are trained on trillions of tokens and are designed to scale across cloud infrastructure, enabling real-time deployment in consumer apps, enterprise tools, and embedded systems. Importantly, many platforms now offer access to generative AI via APIs, such as Google’s Generative AI API and OpenAI’s API suite, allowing developers to easily integrate AI into their applications without deep expertise in machine learning. The democratization of AI tools—offering free tiers and open-source options—further accelerates adoption, making it easier for startups, researchers, and hobbyists to experiment and innovate. In conclusion, generative AI is not just another tech trend—it is a paradigm shift that is redefining creativity, productivity, and intelligence itself. Its impact spans disciplines and demographics, offering both extraordinary potential and considerable risks. As the technology matures, it will be crucial for society to balance innovation with ethics, access with control, and automation with human judgment, ensuring that generative AI benefits humanity in ways that are meaningful, inclusive, and responsible.
"""

spliter=RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter(
    chunk_size=20,
    chunk_overlap=0
)

result=spliter.split_text(text)

print(result)